# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vehicle-dynamics-control
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] An **anti-lock braking system** (**ABS**) is a safety anti-skid braking system used on aircraft and on land vehicles, such as cars, motorcycles, trucks, and buses.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS operates by preventing the wheels from locking up during braking, thereby maintaining tractive contact with the road surface and allowing the driver to maintain more control over the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS is an automated system that uses the principles of threshold braking and cadence braking, techniques which were once practiced by skillful drivers before ABS was widespread.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS operates at a much faster rate and more effectively than most drivers could manage.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Although ABS generally offers improved vehicle control and decreases stopping distances on dry and some slippery surfaces, on loose gravel or snow-covered surfaces ABS may significantly increase braking distance, while still improving steering control.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Since ABS was introduced in production vehicles, such systems have become increasingly sophisticated and effective.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Modern versions may not only prevent wheel lock under braking, but may also alter the front-to-rear brake bias.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This latter function, depending on its specific capabilities and implementation, is known variously as electronic brakeforce distribution, traction control system, emergency brake assist, or electronic stability control (ESC).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The concept for ABS predates the modern systems that were introduced in the 1950s.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Francis introduced his 'Slip Prevention Regulator for Rail Vehicles'.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1920 the French automobile and aircraft pioneer Gabriel Voisin experimented with systems that modulated the hydraulic braking pressure on his aircraft brakes to reduce the risk of tire slippage, as threshold braking on aircraft is nearly impossible.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] These systems used a flywheel and valve attached to a hydraulic line that feeds the brake cylinders.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The flywheel is attached to a drum that runs at the same speed as the wheel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In normal braking, the drum and flywheel should spin at the same speed.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] However, when a wheel slows down, then the drum would do the same, leaving the flywheel spinning at a faster rate.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This causes the valve to open, allowing a small amount of brake fluid to bypass the master cylinder into a local reservoir, lowering the pressure on the cylinder and releasing the brakes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The use of the drum and flywheel meant the valve only opened when the wheel was turning.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In testing, a 30% improvement in braking performance was noted, because the pilots immediately applied full brakes instead of slowly increasing pressure in order to find the skid point.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] An additional benefit was the elimination of burned or burst tires.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The first proper recognition of the ABS system came later with the German engineer Karl Wässel, whose system for modulating braking power was officially patented in 1928.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Wässel, however, never developed a working product and neither did Robert Bosch who produced a similar patent eight years later.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] A similar braking system called Decelostat that used direct-current generators to measure wheel slippage was used in railroads in the 1930s.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] By 1951, flywheel-based Decelostat was used in aircraft to provide anti skid in landings.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The device was on trials first in the United States and later by the British.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1954, *Popular Science* revealed that there was preliminary testing of the Decelostat system to prevent car swirling on a heavy brake by the US car manufacturers in Detroit.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] However, there was no public information of the test results.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Maxaret, while reducing braking distances by up to 30% in icy or wet conditions, also increased tire life, and had the additional advantage of allowing take-offs and landings in conditions that would preclude flying at all in non-Maxaret equipped aircraft.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1958, a Royal Enfield Super Meteor motorcycle was used by the Road Research Laboratory to test the Maxaret anti-lock brake.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The experiments demonstrated that anti-lock brakes can be of great value to motorcycles, for which skidding is involved in a high proportion of accidents.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Stopping distances were reduced in most of the tests compared with locked wheel braking, particularly on slippery surfaces, in which the improvement could be as much as 30%.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Enfield's technical director at the time, Tony Wilson-Jones, saw little future in the system, however, and it was not put into production by the company.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] A fully-mechanical system saw limited automobile use in the 1960s in the Ferguson P99 racing car, the Jensen FF, and the experimental all-wheel drive Ford Zodiac, but saw no further use; the system proved expensive and unreliable.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The first fully-electronic anti-lock braking system was developed in the late-1960s for the Concorde aircraft.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The modern ABS system was invented in 1971 by Mario Palazzetti (known as 'Mister ABS') in the Fiat Research Center and has become standard in almost every car.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The system was called Antiskid and the patent was sold to Bosch who named it ABS.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Chrysler, together with the Bendix Corporation, introduced a computerized, three-channel, four-sensor all-wheel ABS called "Sure Brake" for its 1971 Imperial.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] It was available for several years thereafter, functioned as intended, and proved reliable.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1969, Ford introduced an anti-lock braking system called "Sure-Track" to the rear wheels of the Lincoln Continental Mark III and Ford Thunderbird, as an option; it became standard in 1971.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The Sure-Track braking system was designed with help from Kelsey-Hayes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1971, General Motors introduced the "Trackmaster" rear-wheel only ABS as an option on their rear-wheel drive Cadillac models and called the option the True-Track Braking System on the Oldsmobile Toronado.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1972, the option was made available in all Cadillacs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1971, Nissan offered an EAL (Electro Anti-lock System) developed by Japanese company Denso as an option on the Nissan President, which became Japan's first electronic ABS.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] 1971: The Imperial became the first production car with a 4 wheel computer-operated anti-lock braking system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Toyota introduced electronically controlled anti-skid brakes on Toyota Crown labeled as ESC (Electronic Skid Control).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] 1971: First truck application: "Antislittamento" system developed by *Fiat Veicoli Industriali* and installed on Fiat truck model 691N1.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] 1972: four-wheel-drive Triumph 2500 Estates were fitted with Mullard electronic systems as standard.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Such cars were rare however and very few remain.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] 1976: WABCO began the development of the anti-locking braking system on commercial vehicles to prevent locking on slippery roads, followed in 1986 by the electronic braking system (EBS) for heavy-duty vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] 1978: Mercedes-Benz W116 As one of the firsts, used an electronic four-wheel multi-channel anti-lock braking system (ABS) from Bosch as an option from 1978 on.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] 1982: Honda introduced electronically controlled multi-channel ALB (Anti Locking Brakes) as an option for the second generation of Prelude, launched worldwide in 1982.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Additional info: the general agent for Honda in Norway required all Preludes for the Norwegian market to have the ALB-system as a standard feature, making Honda Prelude be the first car delivered in Europe with ABS as a standard feature.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The Norwegian general agent also included a sunroof and other options to be standard equipment in Norway, adding more luxury to the Honda brand.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] However, the Norwegian tax system made the well-equipped car very expensive, and the sales suffered from high costs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] From 1984 the ALB-system, as well as the other optional features from Honda, was no longer a standard feature in Norway.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1985 the Ford Scorpio was introduced to the European market with a Teves electronic system throughout the range as standard.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] For this the model was awarded the coveted European Car of the Year Award in 1986, with very favorable praise from motoring journalists.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] After this success, Ford began research into Anti-Lock systems for the rest of their range, which encouraged other manufacturers to follow suit.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Since 1987 ABS has been standard equipment on all Mercedes-Benz automobiles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1988, BMW introduced the first motorcycle with an electro-hydraulic ABS: the BMW K100.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Yamaha Introduced the FJ1200 model with optional ABS in 1991.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Honda followed suit in 1992 with the launch of its first motorcycle ABS on the ST1100 Pan European.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 2007, Suzuki launched its GSF1200SA (Bandit) with an ABS.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 2005, Harley-Davidson began offering an ABS option on police bikes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The anti-lock brake controller is also known as the CAB (Controller Anti-lock Brake).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Typically ABS includes a central electronic control unit (ECU), four wheel speed sensors, and at least two hydraulic valves within the brake hydraulics.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Conversely, if the ECU detects a wheel turning significantly faster than the others, brake hydraulic pressure to the wheel is increased so the braking force is reapplied, slowing down the wheel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This process is repeated continuously and can be detected by the driver via brake pedal pulsation.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Some anti-lock systems can apply or release braking pressure 15 times per second.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Because of this, the wheels of cars equipped with ABS are practically impossible to lock even during panic braking in extreme conditions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The ECU is programmed to disregard differences in wheel rotative speed below a critical threshold because when the car is turning, the two wheels towards the center of the curve turn slower than the outer two.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] For this same reason, a differential is used in virtually all roadgoing vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] If a fault develops in any part of the ABS, a warning light will usually be illuminated on the vehicle instrument panel, and the ABS will be disabled until the fault is rectified.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Modern ABS applies individual brake pressure to all four wheels through a control system of hub-mounted sensors and a dedicated micro-controller.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS is offered or comes standard on most road vehicles and is the foundation for electronic stability control systems, which are rapidly increasing in popularity due to the great reduction in the price of vehicle electronics over the years.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Modern electronic stability control (ESC) systems are an evolution of the ABS concept.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Here, a minimum of two additional sensors are added to help the system work: these are a steering wheel angle sensor and a gyroscopic sensor.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The steering wheel sensor also helps in the operation of Cornering Brake Control (CBC), since this will tell the ABS that wheels on the inside of the curve should brake more than wheels on the outside, and by how much.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS equipment may also be used to implement a traction control system (TCS) on the acceleration of the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] If, when accelerating, the tire loses traction, the ABS controller can detect the situation and take suitable action so that traction is regained.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] More sophisticated versions of this can also control throttle levels and brakes simultaneously.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The speed sensors of ABS are sometimes used in indirect tire pressure monitoring system (TPMS), which can detect under-inflation of the tire(s) by the difference in the rotational speed of wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] There are four main components of ABS: wheel speed sensors, valves, a pump, and a controller.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] A speed sensor is used to determine the acceleration or deceleration of the wheel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The rotation of the wheel or differential induces a magnetic field around the sensor.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The fluctuations of this magnetic field generate a voltage in the sensor.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Since the voltage induced in the sensor is a result of the rotating wheel, this sensor can become inaccurate at slow speeds.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The slower rotation of the wheel can cause inaccurate fluctuations in the magnetic field and thus cause inaccurate readings to the controller.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] There is a valve in the brake line of each brake controlled by the ABS.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The majority of problems with the valve system occur due to clogged valves.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] When a valve is clogged it is unable to open, close, or change position.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] An inoperable valve will prevent the system from modulating the valves and controlling pressure supplied to the brakes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The pump in the ABS is used to restore the pressure to the hydraulic brakes after the valves have released it.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] A signal from the controller will release the valve at the detection of wheel slip.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] After a valve releases the pressure supplied from the user, the pump is used to restore the desired amount of pressure to the braking system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The controller will modulate the pump's status in order to provide the desired amount of pressure and reduce slipping.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] type unit in the car which receives information from each individual wheel speed sensor.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] If a wheel loses traction, the signal is sent to the controller.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The controller will then limit the brake force (EBD) and activate the ABS modulator which actuates the braking valves on and off.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] There are many different variations and control algorithms for use in ABS.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The ABS controller knows that such a rapid deceleration of the car is impossible (and in actuality the rapid deceleration means the wheel is about to slip), so it reduces the pressure to that brake until it sees an acceleration, then it increases the pressure until it sees the deceleration again.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] It can do this very quickly before the wheel can actually significantly change speed.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The result is that the wheel slows down at the same rate as the car, with the brakes keeping the wheels very near the point at which they will start to lock up.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This gives the system maximum braking power.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This replaces the need to manually pump the brakes while driving on a slippery or a low traction surface, allowing to steer even in most emergency braking conditions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] When the ABS is in operation the driver will feel a pulsing in the brake pedal; this comes from the rapid opening and closing of the valves.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This pulsing also tells the driver that the ABS has been triggered.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Anti-lock braking systems use different schemes depending on the type of brakes in use.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] They can be differentiated by the number of channels: that is, how many valves that are individually controlled—and the number of speed sensors.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] There is a speed sensor on all four wheels and a separate valve for all four wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] With this setup, the controller monitors each wheel individually to make sure it is achieving maximum braking force.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] There is a speed sensor on all four wheels and a separate valve for each of the front wheels, but only one valve for both of the rear wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Older vehicles with four-wheel ABS usually use this type.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This scheme, commonly found on pickup trucks with four-wheel ABS, has a speed sensor and a valve for each of the front wheels, with one valve and one sensor for both rear wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The speed sensor for the rear wheels is located in the rear axle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This system provides individual control of the front wheels, so they can both achieve maximum braking force.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The rear wheels, however, are monitored together; they both have to start to lock up before the ABS will activate on the rear.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] With this system, it is possible that one of the rear wheels will lock during a stop, reducing brake effectiveness.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This system is easy to identify, as there are no individual speed sensors for the rear wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This system, commonly found on passenger cars from the late '80s through the mid-1990s, uses a speed sensor at each wheel, with one control valve each for the front and rear wheels as a pair.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] If the speed sensor detects lock up at any individual wheel, the control module pulses the valve for both wheels on that end of the car.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This system is commonly found on pickup trucks, SUVs, and vans with rear-wheel ABS.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] It has one valve, which controls both rear wheels, and a one-speed sensor, for the rear axle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This system operates the same as the rear end of a three-channel system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The rear wheels are monitored together and they both have to start to lock up before the ABS kicks in.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In this system it is also possible that one of the rear wheels will lock, reducing brake effectiveness.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This system is also easy to identify, as there are no individual speed sensors for any of the wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] On high-traction surfaces such as bitumen, or concrete, many (though not all) ABS-equipped cars are able to attain braking distances better (i.e. shorter) than those that would be possible without the benefit of ABS.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In real-world conditions, even an alert and experienced driver without ABS would find it difficult to match or improve on the performance of a typical driver with a modern ABS-equipped vehicle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS reduces the chances of crashing, and/or the severity of impact.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The recommended technique for non-expert drivers in an ABS-equipped car, in a typical full-braking emergency, is to press the brake pedal as firmly as possible and, where appropriate, to steer around obstructions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In such situations, ABS will significantly reduce the chances of a skid and subsequent loss of control.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In gravel, sand, and deep snow, ABS tends to increase braking distances.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] On these surfaces, locked wheels dig in and stop the vehicle more quickly.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Some ABS calibrations reduce this problem by slowing the cycling time, thus letting the wheels repeatedly briefly lock and unlock.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Some vehicle manufacturers provide an "off-road" button to turn the ABS function off.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The primary benefit of ABS on such surfaces is to increase the ability of the driver to maintain control of the car rather than go into a skid, though the loss of control remains more likely on soft surfaces such as gravel or on slippery surfaces such as snow or ice.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] On a very slippery surface such as sheet ice or gravel, it is possible to lock multiple wheels at once, and this can defeat ABS (which relies on comparing all four wheels and detecting individual wheels skidding).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The availability of ABS relieves most drivers from learning threshold braking.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] A June 1999 National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) study found that ABS increased stopping distances on loose gravel by an average of 27.2 percent.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] When activated, some earlier ABSes caused the brake pedal to pulse noticeably.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] As most drivers rarely or do not brake hard enough to cause brake lock-up, and drivers typically do not read the vehicle's owner's manual, this may not be noticeable until an emergency.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Some manufacturers have therefore implemented a brake assist system that determines that the driver is attempting a "panic stop" (by detecting that the brake pedal was depressed very quickly, unlike a normal stop where the pedal pressure would usually be gradually increased.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Some systems additionally monitor the rate at the accelerator was released, and/or the time between accelerator release and brake application) and the system automatically increases braking force where not enough pressure is applied.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Hard or panic braking on bumpy surfaces, because of the bumps causing the speed of the wheel(s) to become erratic may also trigger the ABS, sometimes causing the system to enter its ice mode, where the system severely limits maximum available braking power.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Nevertheless, ABS significantly improves safety and control for drivers in most on-road situations.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Anti-lock brakes are the subject of some experiments centred around risk compensation theory, which asserts that drivers adapt to the safety benefit of ABS by driving more aggressively.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In a Munich study, half a fleet of taxicabs was equipped with anti-lock brakes, while the other half had conventional brake systems.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The Insurance Institute for Highway Safety released a study in 2010 that found motorcycles with ABS 37% less likely to be involved in a fatal crash than models without ABS.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] On a motorcycle, an anti-lock brake system prevents the wheels of a motorcycle from locking during braking situations.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Based on information from wheel speed sensors the ABS unit adjusts the pressure of the brake fluid in order to keep traction during deceleration to avoid accidents.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Motorcycle ABS helps the rider to maintain stability during braking and to decrease the stopping distance.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] It provides traction even on low friction surfaces.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] While older ABS models are derived from cars, recent Motorcycle ABS is the result of research, oriented to the specifics of motorcycles in case of size, weight, and functionality.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] National and international organizations have evaluated Motorcycle ABS to be an important factor in increasing safety and reducing the number and severity of motorcycle crashes and collisions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The European Commission passed legislation in 2012 that made the fitment with ABS for all new motorcycles above 125cc to be mandatory from 1 January 2016.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] *Consumer Reports* said in 2016 that "ABS is commonly offered on large, expensive models, but it has been spreading to several entry-level sportbikes and midsized bikes".
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1988, BMW introduced an electronic/hydraulic ABS for motorcycles, ten years after Daimler Benz and Bosch released the first four-wheel vehicle ABS for series production.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Motorcycles of BMW K100 series were optionally equipped with the ABS, which added 11 kg to the bike.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] It was developed together with FAG Kugelfischer and regulated the pressure in the braking circuits via a plunger piston.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Japanese manufacturers followed with an ABS option by 1992 on the Honda ST1100 and the Yamaha FJ1200.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Continental presented its first Motorcycle Integral ABS (MIB) in 2006.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] It has been developed in cooperation with BMW and weighed 2.3 kg.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] While the first generation of motorcycle ABS weighed around 11 kg, the generation (2011) presented by Bosch in 2009 weighs 0.7 kg (ABS base) and 1.6 kg (ABS enhanced) with integral braking.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Wheel speed sensors mounted on the front and rear wheel constantly measures the rotational speed of each wheel and delivers this information to an Electronic Control Unit (ECU).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The ECU detects two things: 1) if the deceleration of one wheel exceeds a fixed threshold and 2) whether the brake slip, calculated based on information of both wheels, rises above a certain percentage and enters an unstable zone.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] These are indicators for a high possibility of a locking wheel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] To countermeasure these irregularities the ECU signals the hydraulic unit to hold or to release pressure.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] After signals show the return to the stable zone, the pressure is increased again.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Past models used a piston for the control of the fluid pressure.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Most recent models regulate the pressure by rapidly opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] While the basic principle and architecture has been carried over from passenger car ABS, typical motorcycle characteristics have to be considered during the development and application processes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] One characteristic is the change of the dynamic wheel load during braking.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Compared to cars, the wheel load changes are more drastic, which can lead to a wheel lift up and a fall over.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This can be intensified by a soft suspension.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Some systems are equipped with a rear-wheel lift-off mitigation functionality.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] When the indicators of a possible rear lift-off are detected, the system releases brake pressure on the front wheel to counter this behavior.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Another difference is that in the case of the motorcycle the front wheel is much more important for stability than the rear wheel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] If the front wheel locks up between 0.2-0.7s, it loses gyrostatic forces and the motorcycle starts to oscillate because of the increased influence of side forces operating on the wheel contact line.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The motorcycle becomes unstable and falls.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Electric vehicles can recapture the energy from rear wheel braking.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Contrary to how the wheels on cars and trains react collectively to brakes when applied, on motorcycles the rear wheel brake and front wheel brake are controlled separately.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] If the rider only brakes with one wheel, this braked wheel tends to lock up faster than if both brakes had been applied.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] A Combined Braking System therefore distributes the brake force also to the non-braked wheel to lower the possibility of a lock-up, increase deceleration and reduce suspension pitch.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] With a single [rear] CBS the brake pressure applied on the rear brake (pedal) is simultaneously distributed to the front wheel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] A delay valve cuts the hydraulic pressure to assure that only when strong braking is applied, the pressure is also created at the front wheel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Honda's first street motorcycle with a combined braking system (then called Unified Braking) was the 1983 GL1100.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This system was derived from the 1970s RCB1000 world endurance race bike.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Larger models with two front discs use a dual CBS System.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The system was first installed by Moto Guzzi in 1975.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Here, applied brake pressure at the front is also applied to the rear wheel and vice versa.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] If the front lever is applied, the pressure is built up at 4 of the 6 pots in the 2 calipers at the front.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] A secondary master cylinder at the front wheel distributes remaining pressure to the rear wheel through a proportional control valve and acts on 2 of the 3 calipers.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] If a strong brake force is applied at the rear wheel force is also distributed to 2 of the 6 pots of the front wheel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] More modern dual CBS use front and rear calipers (and all pots) according to a preset load ratio of front to rear.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The proportioning was originally controlled by complex all-hydraulic systems interlinking the front and rear, with a fixed delay or by sensing weight distribution changes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] As early as 2001 an electrohydraulic system was introduced by BMW.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] CBS helps to reduce the danger of wheel locks and fall downs but in certain situations, it is possible that CBS causes a fall down.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] If brake pressure is distributed from the rear wheel to the front wheel and the friction of the surfaces changes suddenly (puddle, ice on the street) the front wheel might lock even if only the rear brake has been applied.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This would lead to a loss of stability and a fall down.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] CBS is therefore combined with ABS to avoid this on a motorcycle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Different approaches are possible to realize this combination: *Without active pressure Build up* Single Version: A third additional channel links the rear wheel circuit through a delay valve to the front brake.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Strong brake pressure at the rear wheel (or both wheels) pressurizes both brake circuits however this pressure is adjusted according to wheel speed and brake slip.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The brake input of the rider is measured by pressure sensors and the information is provided to an ECU.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Together with the information of the wheel speed sensors, the ECU calculates the optimal distribution of pressure to prevent lockups and to provide the best possible deceleration.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Based on this output a motor for each wheel operates a pump that builds up and regulates the brake pressure on the wheel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] This system offers a fast reaction time because of the brake by wire functionality.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The MIB (Motorcycle integral Braking system) from Continental Teves and the eCBS (electronic CBS) in the enhanced Motorcycle ABS from Bosch are results of another approach.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] These systems are based on the pump and valve approach.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Through additional valves, stronger pumps and a more powerful motor the system can actively build up pressure.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The input pressure of the rider is measured with pressure sensors at the lever and pedal.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The pump then builds up additional pressure adjusted to riding conditions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] A partial integral system is designed for working in one direction only: front→rear or rear→front.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] A fully integrated system works in both directions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Because these systems are electronically controlled and are able to build up pressure actively, they offer the opportunity to adjust the motorcycle braking behavior to the rider.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] CBS and ABS can be switched off by experienced riders and also different regulation modes with higher and lower thresholds can be chosen, such as the rain or slick mode in the BMW S1000RR.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] These studies caused the EU commission to initiate a legislative process in 2010 that was passed in 2012 and led to ABS for motorcycles above 125 cm3 becoming mandatory from 2016 onwards.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Organizations like the Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile and the Institute of advanced Motorists (IAM) demanded the implementation of this legislation already for 2015.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] On the other hand, some motorcycle riders are protesting against a compulsory ABS for all bikes because they call for a possibility to switch the system off, for off-road usage or for other reasons.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In 2011 the United Nations (UN) started the Decade of Action for Road Safety.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] The main goal is to save 5 million lives until 2020 through global cooperation.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] One part of their global plan is to: Encourage universal deployment of crash avoidance technologies with proven effectiveness such as Electronic Stability Control and Anti-Lock Braking Systems in motorcycles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] In the United States, the NHTSA has mandated ABS in conjunction with electronic stability control under the provisions of FMVSS 126 as of September 1, 2012.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS is required in all new passenger cars produced in the EU since 2003.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Since 2016, the EU has required ABS on all new scooters, motorcycles, tricycles, and quads from 125 cc, otherwise CBS (or ABS).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] 78, related to the braking of vehicles of categories L1, L2, L3, L4 and L5 (motorbikes) is applied by the European Union, Russia, Japan, Turkey, Ukraine, Australia and the United Kingdom.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Global technical regulation number 3 related to Motorcycle brake systems is applied by Canada, the European Union, Japan, Russia, and the United States.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Since 1 April 2019, India has required at least single-channel ABS on all new two-wheelers from 125 cc, otherwise CBS (or ABS).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS has also been mandatory on all new cars and mini-buses from the same date.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Since 1 January 2019, Brazil has required ABS on all new motorcycles from 300 cc.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS has been mandatory on all new cars since January 2014.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] Since 1 January 2024, Argentina has required ABS on all new motorcycles from 250 cc, otherwise CBS (or front wheel ABS) for on-road between 50 and 250cc or their electric equivalents.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS has been mandatory on all new normal cars since January 2014.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] From February 2025, Chile will require ABS on all new motorcycles from 150 cc or 11 kW, otherwise CBS (or ABS) from 50 cc or 4 kW from February 2026.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS has been mandatory on all new cars since October 2020.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] From October 2025, Colombia will require ABS on all new motorcycles from 150 cc or 11 kW, otherwise CBS (or ABS) from 50 cc or 4 kW.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/anti-lock-braking-system] From March 2027, Colombia will require ABS on all new motorcycles from 125 cc, below that with CBS (or ABS).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety in 2004 and 2006, one-third of fatal accidents could be prevented by the use of this technology.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In Europe the electronic stability program had saved an estimated 15,000 lives as of 2020.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC became mandatory in new cars in Canada, the US, and the European Union in 2011, 2012, and 2014, respectively.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Worldwide, 82 percent of all new passenger cars feature the anti-skid system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In 1983, a four-wheel electronic "Anti-Skid Control" system was introduced on the Toyota Crown.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In 1987, Mercedes-Benz, BMW and Toyota introduced their first traction control systems.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Traction control works by applying individual wheel braking and throttle to maintain traction under acceleration, but unlike ESC, it is not designed to aid in steering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In 1990, Mitsubishi released the Diamante in Japan.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Developed to help the driver maintain the intended line through a corner; an onboard computer monitored several vehicle operating parameters through various sensors.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] When too much throttle had been used when taking a curve, engine output and braking were automatically regulated to ensure the proper line through a curve and to provide the proper amount of traction under various road surface conditions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Although not a 'proper' modern stability control system, trace control monitors steering angle, throttle position and individual wheel speeds, although there is no yaw input.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The TCL system's standard wheel slip control function enabled better traction on slippery surfaces or during cornering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In addition to the system's individual effect, it also worked together with the Diamante's electronically controlled suspension and four-wheel steering to improve total handling and performance.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] BMW, working with Bosch and Continental, developed a system to reduce engine torque to prevent loss of control and applied it to most of the BMW model line for 1992, excluding the E30 and E36.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] This system could be ordered with the winter package, which came with a limited-slip differential, heated seats, and heated mirrors.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] From 1987 to 1992, Mercedes-Benz and Bosch co-developed a system called *Elektronisches Stabilitätsprogramm* ("Electronic Stability Program", trademarked as ESP) to control lateral slippage.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In 1995, three automobile manufacturers introduced ESC systems.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Mercedes-Benz, supplied by Bosch, was the first to implement ESP with their Mercedes-Benz S 600 Coupé.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Toyota's Vehicle Stability Control (VSC) system appeared on the Toyota Crown Majesta in 1995.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] General Motors worked with Delphi Automotive and introduced its version of ESC, called "StabiliTrak", in 1996 for the 1997 model year on select Cadillac models.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] StabiliTrak was made standard equipment on all GM SUVs and vans sold in the U.S. and Canada by 2007, except for certain commercial and fleet vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] While the StabiliTrak name is used on most General Motors vehicles for the U.S. market, "Electronic Stability Control" is used for GM's overseas brands, such as Opel, Holden and Saab, except in the cases of Saab's 9-7X and 9-4X (which also use the StabiliTrak name).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The same year, Cadillac introduced an integrated vehicle handling and software control system called the Integrated Chassis Control System (ICCS), on the Cadillac Eldorado.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In 1997, Audi introduced the first series production ESP for all-wheel drive vehicles (Audi A8 and Audi A6 with quattro (four-wheel drive system)).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In 1998, Volvo Cars began to offer their version of ESC called Dynamic Stability and Traction Control (DSTC) on the new Volvo S80.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Meanwhile, others investigated and developed their own systems.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] During a moose test, Swedish journalist Robert Collin of *Teknikens Värld* rolled a Mercedes A-Class (without ESC) at 78 km/h in October 1997.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Because Mercedes Benz promoted a reputation for safety, they recalled and retrofitted 130,000 A-Class cars with firmer suspension and sportier tyres; all newly produced A- class featured ESC as standard along with the upgraded suspension and wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] This produced a significant reduction in crashes, and the number of vehicles with ESC rose.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The availability of ESC in small cars like the A-Class ignited a market trend; thus, ESC became available for all models (whether standard or as an option).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Ford's version of ESC, called AdvanceTrac, was launched in the year 2000.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Ford later added Roll Stability Control to AdvanceTrac which was first introduced in the Volvo XC90 in 2003.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] It has been implemented in many Ford vehicles since.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Ford and Toyota announced that all their North American vehicles would be equipped with ESC standard by the end of 2009 (it was standard on Toyota SUVs as of 2004, and after the 2011 model year, all Lexus, Toyota, and Scion vehicles had ESC; the last one to get it was the 2011 model-year Scion tC).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] However, as of November 2010, Ford still sold models in North America without ESC.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] General Motors had made a similar announcement for the end of 2010.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In 2003 in Sweden the purchase rate on new cars with ESC was 15%.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The Swedish road safety administration issued a strong ESC recommendation and in September 2004, 16 months later, the purchase rate was 58%.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] A stronger ESC recommendation was then given and in December 2004, the purchase rate on new cars had reached 69% and by 2008 it had grown to 96%.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC advocates around the world are promoting increased ESC use through legislation and public awareness campaigns and by 2012, most new vehicles should be equipped with ESC.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In 2009, the European Union decided to make ESC mandatory.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Since November 1, 2011, EU type approval is only granted to models equipped with ESC.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Since November 1, 2014, ESC has been required on all newly registered cars in the EU.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The NHTSA required all new passenger vehicles sold in the US to be equipped with ESC as of the 2012 model year, and estimated it will prevent 5,300–9,600 annual fatalities.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] During normal driving, ESC continuously monitors steering and vehicle direction.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] It compares the driver's intended direction (determined by the measured steering wheel angle) to the vehicle's actual direction (determined through measured lateral acceleration, vehicle rotation, and individual road wheel speeds).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC intervenes only when it detects a probable loss of steering control, such as when the vehicle is not going where the driver is steering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] This may happen, for example, when skidding during emergency evasive swerves, understeer or oversteer during poorly judged turns on slippery roads, or hydroplaning.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] During high-performance driving, ESC can intervene when unwanted, because steering input may not always be indicative of the intended direction of travel (such as during controlled drifting).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC estimates the direction of the skid, and then applies the brakes to individual wheels asymmetrically in order to create torque about the vehicle's vertical axis, opposing the skid and bringing the vehicle back in line with the driver's commanded direction.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Additionally, the system may reduce engine power or operate the transmission to slow the vehicle down.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC can function on any surface, from dry pavement to frozen lakes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] It reacts to and corrects skidding much faster and more effectively than the typical human driver, often before the driver is even aware of any imminent loss of control.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] This has led to some concern that ESC could allow drivers to become overconfident in their vehicle's handling and/or their own driving skills.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] For this reason, ESC systems typically alert the driver when they intervene, so that the driver is aware that the vehicle's handling limits have been reached.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Most activate a dashboard indicator light and/or alert tone; some intentionally allow the vehicle's corrected course to deviate very slightly from the driver-commanded direction, even if it is possible to more precisely match it.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] All ESC manufacturers emphasize that the system is not a performance enhancement nor a replacement for safe driving practices, but rather a safety technology to assist the driver in recovering from dangerous situations.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC does not increase traction, so it does not enable faster cornering (although it can facilitate better-controlled cornering).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] More generally, ESC works within the limits of the vehicle's handling and available traction between the tyres and road.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] A reckless maneuver can still exceed these limits, resulting in loss of control.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] For example, during hydroplaning, the wheels that ESC would use to correct a skid may lose contact with the road surface, reducing its effectiveness.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Due to the fact that stability control can be incompatible with high-performance driving, many vehicles have an override control which allows the system to be partially or fully deactivated.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In simple systems, a single button may disable all features, while more complicated setups may have a multi-position switch or may never be fully disengaged.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC systems—due to their ability to enhance vehicle stability and braking—often work to improve traction in off-road situations, in addition to their on-road duties.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The effectiveness of traction control systems can vary significantly, due to the significant number of external and internal factors involved at any given time, as well as the programming and testing performed by the manufacturer.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] At a rudimentary level, off-road traction varies from typical operational characteristics of on-road traction, depending on the terrain encountered.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In an open differential setup, power transfer takes the path of least resistance.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In slippery conditions, this means when one wheel loses traction, power will counter-productively be fed to that axle instead of the one with higher grip.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESCs focus on braking wheels that are spinning at a rate drastically different from the opposing axle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In intermediate level ESC systems, ABS will be disabled, or the computer will actively lock the wheels when brakes are applied.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In these systems, or in vehicles without ABS, the performance in emergency braking in slippery conditions is greatly improved as grip state can change extremely rapidly and unpredictably off-road when coupled with inertia.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] When the brakes are applied and wheels are locked, the tyres do not have to contend with the wheel rolling (providing no braking force) and braking repeatedly.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Grip provided by the tyres is constant and as such can make full use of traction wherever it is available.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] This effect is enhanced where more aggressive tread patterns are present as the large tread lugs dig into the imperfections on the surface or below the substrate, as well as dragging dirt in front of the tyre to increase the rolling resistance even further.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Many newer vehicles designed for off-road duties from the factory, are equipped with Hill Descent Control systems to minimise the risk of such runaway events occurring with novice drivers and provide a more consistent and safe descent than either no ABS, or on-road orientated ABS.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] These systems aim to keep a fixed speed (or user selected speed) while descending, applying strategic braking or acceleration at the correct moments to ensure wheels all rotate at the same rate while applying full locking braking when required.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In some vehicles, ESC systems automatically detect whether to operate in off- or on-road mode, depending on the engagement of the 4WD system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Mitsubishi's unique Super-Select 4WD system (found in Pajero, Triton and Pajero Sport models), operates in on-road mode in 2WD as well as 4WD High-range with the centre differential unlocked.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] However, it automatically activates off-road traction control and disables ABS braking when shifted into 4WD High-range with centre differential locked, or 4WD Low-range with centre differential locked.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Most modern vehicles with fully electronically controlled 4WD systems such as various Land Rovers and Range Rovers, also automatically switch to an off-road-orientated mode of stability and traction control once low range, or certain terrain modes are manually selected.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Numerous studies around the world have confirmed that ESC is highly effective in helping the driver maintain control of the car, thereby saving lives and reducing the probability of occurrence and severity of crashes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In the fall of 2004, the American National Highway and Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) confirmed international studies, releasing results of a field study of ESC effectiveness in the USA.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The NHTSA concluded that ESC reduces crashes by 35%.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Additionally, SUVs with stability control are involved in 67% fewer accidents than SUVs without the system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The United States Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS) issued its own study in June 2006 showing that up to 10,000 fatal US crashes could be avoided annually if all vehicles were equipped with ESC.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The IIHS study concluded that ESC reduces the likelihood of all fatal crashes by 43%, fatal single-vehicle crashes by 56%, and fatal single-vehicle rollovers by 77–80%.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The European New Car Assessment Program (Euro NCAP) "strongly recommends" that people buy cars fitted with stability control.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The IIHS requires that a vehicle must have ESC as an available option in order for it to qualify for their *Top Safety Pick* award for occupant protection and accident avoidance.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC incorporates yaw rate control into the anti-lock braking system (ABS).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Anti-lock brakes enable ESC to slow down individual wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Many ESC systems also incorporate a traction control system (TCS or ASR), which senses drive-wheel slip under acceleration and individually brakes the slipping wheel or wheels and/or reduces excess engine power until control is regained.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] However, ESC serves a different purpose from that of ABS or traction control.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The ESC system uses several sensors to determine where the driver intends to travel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Other sensors indicate the actual state of the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The control algorithm compares driver input to vehicle response and decides, when necessary, to apply brakes and/or reduce throttle by the amounts calculated through the state space (set of equations used to model the dynamics of the vehicle).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The ESC controller can also receive data from and issue commands to other controllers on the vehicle such as an all-wheel drive system or an active suspension system to improve vehicle stability and controllability.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The sensors in an ESC system have to send data at all times in order to detect a loss of traction as soon as possible.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] They have to be resistant to possible forms of interference, such as precipitation or potholes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC uses a hydraulic modulator to assure that each wheel receives the correct brake force.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Whereas ABS reduces hydraulic pressure during braking, ESC may increase pressure in certain situations, and an active vacuum brake booster unit may be utilised in addition to the hydraulic pump to meet these demanding pressure gradients.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] At the centre of the ESC system is the electronic control unit (ECU), which contains various control techniques.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Often, the same ECU is used for different systems at the same time (such as ABS, traction control, or climate control).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The input signals are sent through an input circuit to the digital controller.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The desired vehicle state is determined based upon the steering wheel angle, its gradient, and the wheel speed.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Simultaneously, the yaw sensor measures the vehicle's actual yaw rate.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The controller computes the needed brake or acceleration force for each wheel and directs the valves of the hydraulic modulator.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The ECU is connected with other systems via a Controller Area Network interface in order to avoid conflicting with them.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Many ESC systems have an override switch so the driver can disable ESC, which may be used on loose surfaces such as mud or sand, or if using a small spare tire, which could interfere with the sensors.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Some systems also offer an additional mode with raised thresholds, so that a driver can utilize the limits of their vehicle's grip with less electronic intervention.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] However, the ESC reactivates when the ignition is restarted.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Some ESC systems that lack an off switch, such as on many recent Toyota and Lexus vehicles, can be temporarily disabled through an undocumented series of brake pedal and handbrake operations.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] While Sweden used public awareness campaigns to promote ESC use, others implemented or proposed legislation.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The Canadian province of Quebec was the first jurisdiction to implement an ESC law, making it compulsory for carriers of dangerous goods (without data recorders) in 2005.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The United States followed, with the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration implementing FMVSS 126, which requires ESC for all passenger vehicles under 10,000 pounds (4536 kg).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The regulation phased in starting with 55% of 2009 models (effective 1 September 2008), 75% of 2010 models, 95% of 2011 models, and all 2012 and later models.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The standard endorses the use of the Sine with Dwell test.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In 2015 NHTSA finalized updated regulations requiring ESC for truck tractors and certain buses.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Canada required all new passenger vehicles to have ESC from 1 September 2011.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The New Zealand government followed suit in February 2014 making it compulsory on all new vehicles from 1 July 2015 with a staggered roll-out to all used-import passenger vehicles by 1 January 2020.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The European Parliament has also called for the accelerated introduction of ESC.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The European Commission has confirmed a proposal for the mandatory introduction of ESC on all new cars and commercial vehicle models sold in the EU from 2012, with all new cars being equipped by 2014.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Argentina requires all new normal cars to have ESC since 1 January 2022, for all new normal vehicles from January 2024.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Chile requires all new cars to have ESC from August 2022.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Brazil has required all new cars to have ESC from 1 January 2024.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The United Nations Economic Commission for Europe has passed a Global Technical Regulation to harmonize ESC standards.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] 8 ELECTRONIC STABILITY CONTROL SYSTEMS was sponsored by the United States of America, and is based on Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard FMVSS 126.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In Unece countries, approval is based on UN Regulation 140: Electronic Stability Control (ESC) Systems.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC is built on top of an anti-lock brake system, and all ESC-equipped vehicles are fitted with traction control.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC components include a yaw rate sensor, a lateral acceleration sensor, a steering wheel sensor, and an upgraded integrated control unit.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In the US, federal regulations have required that ESC be installed as a standard feature on all passenger cars and light trucks as of the 2012 model year.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] According to NHTSA research, ABS in 2005 cost an estimated US$368; ESC cost a further US$111.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The retail price of ESC varies; as a stand-alone option it retails for as little as US$250.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC was once rarely offered as a sole option, and was generally not available for aftermarket installation.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Instead, it was frequently bundled with other features or more expensive trims, so the cost of a package that included ESC was several thousand dollars.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Nonetheless, ESC is considered highly cost-effective and may pay for itself in reduced insurance premiums.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Availability of ESC in passenger vehicles has varied between manufacturers and countries.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In 2007, ESC was available in roughly 50% of new North American models compared to about 75% in Sweden.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] However, consumer awareness affects buying patterns, so that roughly 45% of vehicles sold in North America and the UK were purchased with ESC, contrasting with 78–96% in other European countries such as Germany, Denmark, and Sweden.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] While few vehicles had ESC prior to 2004, increased awareness has increased the number of vehicles with ESC on the used car market.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC is available on cars, SUVs and pickup trucks from all major automakers.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Luxury cars, sports cars, SUVs, and crossovers are usually equipped with ESC.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Midsize cars have also been gradually catching on, though the 2008 model years of the Nissan Altima and Ford Fusion only offered ESC on their V6 engine-equipped cars; however, some midsize cars, such as the Honda Accord, had it as standard by then.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] While traction control is usually included with ESC, there were vehicles such as the 2008 Chevrolet Malibu LS, 2008 Mazda6, and 2007 Lincoln MKZ that had traction control but not ESC.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC was rare among subcompact cars in 2008.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The 2009 Toyota Corolla in the United States (but not Canada) had stability control as a $250 option on all trims below that of the XRS, which had it as standard.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In Canada, for the 2010 Mazda3, ESC was an option on the midrange GS trim as part of its sunroof package, and is standard on the top-of-the-line GT version.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In the UK, even mass-market superminis such as the Ford Fiesta Mk.6 and VW Polo Mk.5 came with ESC as standard.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Elaborate ESC and ESP systems (including Roll Stability Control) are available for many commercial vehicles, including transport trucks, trailers, and buses from manufacturers such as Daimler, Scania, and Prevost.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In heavy trucks the ESC and ESP functions must be realized as part of the pneumatic brake system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Typical component and system suppliers are e.g.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] ESC is also available on some motor homes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The *ChooseESC!* campaign, run by the EU's *eSafetyAware!* project, provides a global perspective on ESC.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] One *ChooseESC!* publication shows the availability of ESC in EU member countries.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In the US, the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety website shows availability of ESC in individual US models and the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration website lists US models with ESC.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] In Australia, the NRMA shows the availability of ESC in Australian models.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Just as ESC is founded on the anti-lock braking system (ABS), ESC is the foundation for new advances such as Roll Stability Control or active rollover protection that works in the vertical plane much like ESC works in the horizontal plane.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] When RSC detects impending rollover (usually on transport trucks or SUVs), RSC applies brakes, reduces throttle, induces understeer, and/or slows down the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] The computing power of ESC facilitates the networking of active and passive safety systems, addressing other causes of crashes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] For example, sensors may detect when a vehicle is following too closely and slow down the vehicle, straighten up seat backs, and tighten seat belts, avoiding and/or preparing for a crash.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Moreover, current research on electronic stability control focuses on the integration of information: i) from systems from multiple domains within the same vehicle, for example radars, cameras, lidars and navigation system; and ii) from other vehicles, road users and infrastructure.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/electronic-stability-control] Electronic stability control (ESC) is the generic term recognised by the European Automobile Manufacturers Association (ACEA), the North American Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE), the Japan Automobile Manufacturers Association, and other worldwide authorities.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Aircraft flight control systems are normally steered when airborne by the use of ailerons, spoileron, or both to bank the aircraft into a turn; although the rudder can also be used to turn the aircraft, it is usually used to minimize adverse yaw, rather than as a means to directly cause the turn.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] On the ground, aircraft are generally steered at low speeds by turning the nosewheel or tailwheel (using a tiller or the rudder pedals) or through differential braking, and by the rudder at high speeds.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Missiles, airships and large hovercraft are usually steered by a rudder, thrust vectoring, or both.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Small sport hovercraft have similar rudders, but steer mostly by the pilot shifting their weight from side to side and unbalancing the more powerful lift forces beneath the skirt.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Jet packs and flying platforms are steered by thrust vectoring only.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Helicopter flight controls are steered by cyclic control, changing the thrust vector of the main rotor(s), and by anti-torque control, usually provided by a tail rotor.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] A conventional automotive steering arrangement allows a driver to control the direction of the vehicle by turning the direction of the front wheels using a hand–operated steering wheel positioned in front of the driver.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The steering wheel is attached to a steering column, which is linked to rods, pivots and gears that allow the driver to change the direction of the front wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The mechanism may include a rack and pinion mechanism that converts several turns of the steering wheel into a large linear displacement.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Alternatively, it may use a recirculating ball system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The mechanism may be power-assisted, usually by hydraulic or electrical means.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The use of a variable rack (still using a normal pinion) was invented by Arthur Ernest Bishop in the 1970s, so as to improve vehicle response and aim to allow for more comfortable steering, especially at high speeds.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] He also created a low cost press forging process to manufacture the racks, eliminating the need to machine the gear teeth.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Other arrangements are sometimes found on different types of vehicles; for example, a tiller or rear-wheel steering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Tracked vehicles such as bulldozers and tanks usually employ differential steering, where the tracks are made to move at different speeds or in opposite directions, using the clutch and brakes, to achieve a change of direction.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The basic aim of steering is to ensure that the wheels are pointing in the desired direction to move the vehicle as required.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] This is typically achieved by a series of linkages, rods, pivots, and gears.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] One of the fundamental concepts is that of caster angle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Each wheel is steered with a pivot point ahead of the wheel, which tends to make the steering self-centered in the direction of travel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The angle the wheels make in the vertical plane, known as camber angle, also influences steering dynamics as do the tires.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Steering wheel turning is often measured in terms of number of full 360-degree turns to go **lock-to-lock**.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] This is when the steering input mechanism is restrained at its mechanical limit from the full right-turn stop to the left-turn stop.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Many modern cars have a steering mechanism called a rack and pinion.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The steering wheel turns a pinion gear, which moves a rack back and forth to steer the wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] This mechanism converts the circular motion of the steering wheel to linear motion, which is applied to the wheels of the car via tie rods and a steering knuckle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Rack and pinion steering has several advantages, such as a direct steering "feel".
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] This means that the driver can feel the road better and have more precise control over the car's movement.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] BMW was one of the first manufacturers to adopt rack and pinion steering systems in the 1930s, with many other European manufacturers following suit.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Auto manufacturers in the United States began to use rack and pinion steering with the 1974 Ford Pinto.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Older designs use two main principles: the worm and sector design and the screw and nut.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Both types were enhanced by reducing the friction; for screw and nut it is the recirculating ball mechanism, which is still found on trucks and utility vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The steering column turns a large screw, which meshes with the nut by recirculating balls.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The nut moves a sector of a gear, causing it to rotate about its axis as the screw is turned; an arm attached to the axis of the sector moves the pitman arm, which is connected to the steering linkage and thus steers the wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The recirculating ball version of this apparatus reduces the considerable friction by placing large ball bearings between the screw and the nut.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] At either end of the apparatus, the balls exit from between the two pieces into a channel internal to the box, which connects them with the other end of the apparatus.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] This design is still in use in trucks and other large vehicles, where rapidity of steering and direct feel are less important than robustness, maintainability, and mechanical advantage.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The worm and sector was an older design, used for example in Willys and Chrysler vehicles, and the Ford Falcon (1960s).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] To reduce friction, the sector is replaced by a roller or rotating pins on the rocker shaft arm.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Generally, older vehicles use the recirculating ball mechanism, and only newer vehicles use rack-and-pinion steering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] This division is not very strict, however, and rack-and-pinion steering systems can be found on British sports cars of the mid-1950s, and some German carmakers did not give up recirculating ball technology until the early 1990s.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Other systems for steering exist, but are uncommon on road vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Power steering helps the driver of a vehicle to steer by directing some of its engine power to assist in swiveling the steered road wheels about their steering axes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] To alleviate this, auto makers have developed power steering systems, or more correctly power-assisted steering, since on road-going vehicles there has to be a mechanical linkage as a fail-safe.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] There are two types of power steering systems: hydraulic and electric/electronic.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] A hydraulic-electric hybrid system is also possible.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] A Hydraulic Power Steering (HPS) uses hydraulic pressure supplied by an engine-driven pump to assist the motion of turning the steering wheel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Electric Power Steering (EPS) is more efficient than hydraulic power-steering, since the electric power-steering motor only needs to provide assistance when the steering wheel is turned, whereas the hydraulic pump must run constantly.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] In EPS, the amount of assistance is easily tunable to the vehicle type, road speed, and driver preference.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] An added benefit is the elimination of the environmental hazard posed by leakage and disposal of hydraulic power-steering fluid.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] In addition, electrical assistance is not lost when the engine fails or stalls, whereas hydraulic assistance stops working if the engine stops, making the steering doubly heavy as the driver must now turn not only the very heavy steering—without any help—but also the power-assistance system itself.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Speed-sensitive steering allows for highly assisted steering at low speeds for maneuverability, and lightly assisted steering at high speed for stability.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The first vehicle with this feature was the Citroën SM with its DIRAVI system, first sold in France in 1970.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The hydraulic steering system applied force on a centering cam which pushed the steering rack and wheel back to the straight-ahead position.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The centering force increased with speed, requiring more effort to turn the wheel at greater speeds.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Modern speed-sensitive power steering systems reduce the mechanical or electrical assistance as the vehicle speed increases, giving a more direct feel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] This feature is gradually becoming more common.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] For example, it was used on a production pickup truck, the Tesla Cybertruck, in 2023.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Four-wheel steering is a system employed by some vehicles to improve steering response, increase vehicle stability while maneuvering at high speed, or to decrease turning radius at low speed.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] In an active four-wheel steering system, all four wheels turn at the same time when the driver steers.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] In most active four-wheel steering systems, the rear wheels are steered by a computer and actuators.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The rear wheels generally cannot turn as far as the front wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] There can be controls to switch off the rear steering and options to steer only the rear wheels independently of the front wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Four-wheel steering is used in most monster trucks, where maneuverability in small arenas is critical, and it is also popular in large farm vehicles and trucks.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Some of the modern European Intercity buses also utilize four-wheel steering to assist maneuverability in bus terminals, and also to improve road stability.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Mazda were pioneers in applying four-wheel steering to automobiles, showing it on their 1984 Mazda MX-02 concept car, where the rear wheels counter-steered at low speeds.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Mazda proceeded to offer a version of this electronic four-wheel steering system on the Mazda 626 and MX6 in 1988.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The first rally vehicle to use the technology was the Peugeot 405 Turbo 16, which debuted at the 1988 Pikes Peak International Hill Climb.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Previously, Honda had mechanical four-wheel steering as an option in their 1987–2001 Prelude and Honda Ascot models (1989–1996) later upgrading to electronically controlled.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] General Motors offered Delphi's Quadrasteer in their Silverado/Sierra and Suburban/Yukon.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Due to initially high cost as an option and lack of familiarity producing low demand, GM discontinued the technology at the end of the 2005 model year.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Nissan/Infiniti offer several versions of their HICAS system as standard or as an option in much of their line-up.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] In the early 2000s, a new generation of four-wheel steering systems was introduced into the market.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] In 2001 BMW equipped the E65 7 series with an all-wheel steering system (optional, called 'Integral Active Steering'), which is available on the current 5, 6, and 7 series, as an option.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Renault introduced an optional all-wheel steering called '4control' in 2009, at first on the Laguna GT, which is currently available on the Talisman, Mégane and Espace vehicle lines.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] In 2013, Porsche introduced a system on the 911 Turbo as standard equipment.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Since 2016, the Panamera has been offered with optional all-wheel steering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The 2014 Audi Q7 was launched with an optional system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Also the Japanese OEMs offer luxury segment vehicles equipped with all-wheel steering, such as Infiniti on its QX70 model ('Rear Active Steering') and Lexus on the GS.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Italian manufacturers have launched the technology in the model years 2016–17 with the Ferrari F12tdf, the Ferrari GTC4Lusso as well as the Lamborghini Aventador S.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Crab steering is a special type of active four-wheel steering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] It operates by steering all wheels in the same direction and at the same angle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Crab steering is used when the vehicle needs to proceed in a straight line but at an angle: when changing lanes on a highway at speed, when moving loads with a reach truck, or during filming with a camera dolly.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Rear wheel steering can also be used when the rear wheels may not follow the path taken by the front wheel tracks (e.g. to reduce soil compaction when using rolling farm equipment).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Many modern vehicles have passive rear-wheel steering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] On many vehicles, when cornering, the rear wheels tend to steer slightly to the outside of a turn, which can reduce stability.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The passive steering system uses the lateral forces generated in a turn (through suspension geometry) and the bushings to correct this tendency and steer the wheels slightly to the inside of the corner.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] This improves the stability of the car through the turn.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] This effect is called compliance understeer; it, or its opposite, is present on all suspensions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Typical methods of achieving compliance understeer are to use a Watt's link on a live rear axle, or the use of toe control bushings on a twist beam suspension.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] On an independent rear suspension it is normally achieved by changing the rates of the rubber bushings in the suspension.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Passive rear-wheel steering is not a new concept, as it has been in use for many years, although not always recognized as such.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Articulated steering is a system by which a vehicle is split into front and rear halves which are connected by a vertical hinge.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The front and rear halves are connected with one or more hydraulic cylinders that change the angle between the halves, including the front and rear axles and wheels, thus steering the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] This system does not use steering arms, king pins, tie rods, etc. as does four-wheel steering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] If the vertical hinge is placed equidistant between the two axles, it also eliminates the need for a central differential in four-wheel drive vehicles, as both front and rear axles will follow the same path, and thus rotate at the same speed.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Articulated haulers have very good off-road performance.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Vehicle-trailer-combinations such as semi-trailers, road trains, articulated buses, and internal transport trolley trains can be regarded as passively-articulated vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] A few types of vehicle use only rear-wheel steering, notably fork lift trucks, camera dollies, early pay loaders, Buckminster Fuller's Dymaxion car, and the ThrustSSC.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Rear wheel steering is particularly useful for tight maneuvring.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] However naive implementations of rear-wheel steering tend to oversteer which may lead to steering instability.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Therefore rear-wheel steering usually only found in slower vehicles that need high-maneuverability in tight spaces, e.g. fork lifts.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] For heavy haulage or for increased maneuverability, some semi-trailers are fitted with rear-wheel steering, controlled electro-hydraulically.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The wheels on all or some of the rear axles may be turned through different angles to enable tighter cornering, or through the same angle (crab steering) to move the rear of the trailer laterally.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The aim of steer-by-wire technology is to completely remove as many mechanical components (steering shaft, column, gear reduction mechanism, etc.) as possible.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Steer-by-wire without the use of a steering column was first offered in a production car with the Nissan Infiniti Q50 in 2013.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Steer-by-wire continued to be offered with the QX50 and QX55, and as of 2022 is being offered with the Infiniti Q60 coupe.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Production battery electric vehicles in the 2020s that offer steer-by-wire with no steering column include the Canoo Lifestyle Vehicle, Lexus RZ 450e, REE Automotive P7-module-based vehicles, Toyota bZ4X, and Tesla Cybertruck.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] As of 2023 Lotus, Peugeot, and Mercedes-Benz plan to offer steer-by-wire cars in the mid to late 2020s.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Traditionally, cars feature a collapsible steering column (energy absorbing steering column) which will collapse in the event of a heavy frontal impact to avoid excessive injuries to the driver.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Airbags are also generally fitted as standard.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Non-collapsible steering columns fitted to older vehicles very often impaled drivers in frontal crashes, particularly when the steering box or rack was mounted in front of the front axle line, at the front of the crumple zone.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] This was particularly a problem on vehicles that had a rigid separate chassis frame with no crumple zone.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Many modern vehicle steering boxes or racks are mounted behind the front axle on the front bulkhead, at the rear of the front crumple zone.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Collapsible steering columns were invented by Béla Barényi and were introduced in the 1959 Mercedes-Benz W111 Fintail, along with crumple zones.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] This safety feature first appeared on cars built by General Motors after an extensive and very public lobbying campaign enacted by Ralph Nader.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Ford started to install collapsible steering columns in 1968.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Audi used a retractable steering wheel and seat belt tensioning system called procon-ten, but it has since been discontinued in favor of airbags and pyrotechnic seat belt pre-tensioners.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] In bicycles and motorcycles, leaning in the direction of the turn is required to counter the inertia of the vehicle, which would otherwise cause it to skid in a straight line.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] To make a two-wheeled vehicle lean into a turn, riders often steer briefly in the opposite direction to angle the wheels away from the turn, a process known as countersteering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] At low speeds, the countersteering required to make a turn is almost unnoticeably small, but at a typical motorcycle's speed, large and deliberate countersteering is required to complete a turn quickly.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The amount of countersteering required also depends on the vehicle's weight, as bicycles can often complete turns using only weight shifting.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Similar techinques are also used to steer tilting three-wheeled vehicles, but rigid, non-tilting three-wheelers are steered similarly to cars, and can require differentials so that the wheel facing away from the turn can complete a longer distance than the wheel facing into the turn.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Ships and boats are usually steered with a rudder.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Depending on the size of the vessel, rudders can be manually actuated, or operated using a servomechanism, or a trim tab or servo tab system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Rowing may be used to steer rowboats by using specific paddle strokes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Boats using outboard motors steer by rotating the entire drive unit.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Boats with inboard motors sometimes steer by rotating the propeller pod only (i.e., Volvo Penta IPS drive).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Steering wheels may be used to control the rudder or propeller.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Modern ships with diesel-electric drive use azimuth thrusters.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Boats powered by oars or paddles are steered by generating a higher propulsion force on the side of the boat opposite of the direction of turn.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Jet skis are steered by weight-shift induced roll and water jet thrust vectoring.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The rudder of a vessel can steer the ship only when water is passing over it.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Hence, when a ship is not moving relative to the water it is in or cannot move its rudder, it does not respond to the helm and is said to have *lost steerage*.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] The motion of a ship through the water is known as *making way*.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/steering] Boats on rivers must always be under propulsion, even when traveling downstream, in order to steer, requiring sufficient water to pass over the surface of the rudder to effect changes in the direction of the boat in response to the helm.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] An early form of suspension on ox-drawn carts had the platform swing on iron chains attached to the wheeled frame of the carriage.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This system remained the basis for most suspension systems until the turn of the 19th century, although the iron chains were replaced with the use of leather straps called thoroughbraces by the 17th century.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] No modern automobiles have used the thoroughbrace suspension system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] By approximately 1750, leaf springs began appearing on certain types of carriage, such as the Landau.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] By the middle of the 19th century, elliptical springs might additionally start to be used on carriages.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Automobiles were initially developed as self-propelled versions of horse-drawn vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] However, horse-drawn vehicles had been designed for relatively slow speeds, and their suspension was not well suited to the higher speeds permitted by the internal combustion engine.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The first workable spring-suspension required advanced metallurgical knowledge and skill, and only became possible with the advent of industrialisation.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Obadiah Elliott registered the first patent for a spring-suspension vehicle; each wheel had two durable steel leaf springs on each side and the body of the carriage was fixed directly to the springs which were attached to the axles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Within a decade, most British horse carriages were equipped with springs; wooden springs in the case of light one-horse vehicles to avoid taxation, and steel springs in larger vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] These were often made of low-carbon steel and usually took the form of multiple layer leaf springs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Leaf springs have been around since the early Egyptians.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Ancient military engineers used leaf springs in the form of bows to power their siege engines, with little success at first.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The use of leaf springs in catapults was later refined and made to work years later.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Horse-drawn carriages and Ford Model T used this system, and it is still used today in larger vehicles, mainly mounted in the rear suspension.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Springs were not only made of metal; a sturdy tree branch could be used as a spring, such as with a bow.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Leaf springs were the first modern suspension system, and, along with advances in the construction of roads, heralded the single greatest improvement in road transport until the advent of the automobile.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The British steel springs were not well-suited for use on America's rough roads of the time, so the Abbot-Downing Company of Concord, New Hampshire re-introduced leather strap suspension, which gave a swinging motion instead of the jolting up-and-down of spring suspension.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In 1901, Mors of Paris first fitted an automobile with shock absorbers.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] With the advantage of a damped suspension system on his 'Mors Machine', Henri Fournier won the prestigious Paris-to-Berlin race on 20 June 1901.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Fournier's superior time was 11 hours 46 minutes and 10 seconds, while the best competitor was Léonce Girardot in a Panhard with a time of 12 hours, 15 minutes, and 40 seconds.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Coil springs first appeared on a production vehicle in 1906 in the Brush Runabout made by the Brush Motor Company.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Today, coil springs are used in most cars.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In 1920, Leyland Motors used torsion bars in a suspension system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In 1922, independent front suspension was pioneered on Lancia Lambda, and became more common in mass market cars from 1932.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Today, most cars have independent suspension on all four wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The part on which pre-1950 springs were supported is called a dumb iron.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In 2002, a new passive suspension component, the inerter, was invented by Malcolm C.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This has the ability to increase the effective inertia of wheel suspension using a geared flywheel, but without adding significant mass.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] It was initially employed in Formula One in secrecy, but has since spread to wider motorsport.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] For front-wheel drive cars, rear suspension has few constraints, and a variety of beam axles and independent suspensions are used.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] For rear-wheel drive cars, rear suspension has many constraints, and the development of the superior, but more expensive independent suspension layout has been difficult.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Henry Ford's Model T used a torque tube to restrain this force, for his differential was attached to the chassis by a lateral leaf spring and two narrow rods.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The torque tube surrounded the true driveshaft and exerted the force to its ball joint at the extreme rear of the transmission, which was attached to the engine.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] A similar method like this was used in the late 1930s by Buick and by Hudson's *bathtub car* in 1948, which used helical springs that could not take fore-and-aft thrust.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The Hotchkiss drive, invented by Albert Hotchkiss, was the most popular rear suspension system used in American cars from the 1930s to the 1970s.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The system uses longitudinal leaf springs attached both forward and behind the differential of the live axle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] These springs transmit torque to the frame.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Although scorned by many European car makers of the time, it was accepted by American car makers, because it was inexpensive to manufacture.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Also, the dynamic defects of this design were suppressed by the enormous weight of U.S. passenger vehicles before the implementation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standard.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Another Frenchman invented the De Dion tube, which is sometimes called "semi-independent".
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Like true independent rear suspension, this employs two universal joints, or their equivalent from the centre of the differential to each wheel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] But the wheels cannot entirely rise and fall independently of each other; they are tied by a yoke that goes around the differential, below and behind it.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This method has had little use in the United States.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Its use around 1900 was probably due to the poor quality of tires, which wore out quickly.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] By removing a good deal of unsprung weight, as independent rear suspensions do, it made them last longer.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Rear-wheel drive vehicles today frequently use a fairly complex fully-independent, multi-link suspension to locate the rear wheels securely, while providing decent ride quality.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The spring rate (or suspension rate) is a component in setting the vehicle's ride height or its location in the suspension stroke.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] When a spring is compressed or stretched, the force it exerts, is proportional to its change in length.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The *spring rate* or *spring constant* of a spring is the change in the force it exerts, divided by the change in deflection of the spring.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Vehicles that carry heavy loads, will often have heavier springs to compensate for the additional weight that would otherwise collapse a vehicle to the bottom of its travel (stroke).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Heavier springs are also used in performance applications, where the loading conditions experienced are more significant.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Springs that are too hard or too soft cause the suspension to become ineffective – mostly because they fail to properly isolate the vehicle from the road.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Vehicles that commonly experience suspension loads heavier than normal, have heavy or hard springs, with a spring rate close to the upper limit for that vehicle's weight.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This allows the vehicle to perform properly under a heavy load, when control is limited by the inertia of the load.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Riding in an empty truck meant for carrying loads can be uncomfortable for passengers, because of its high spring rate relative to the weight of the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] A race car could also be described as having heavy springs, and would also be uncomfortably bumpy.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] However, even though we say they both have heavy springs, the actual spring rates for a 2,000 lb (1,000 kg) racecar and a 10,000 lb (5,000 kg) truck are very different.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] A luxury car, taxi, or passenger bus would be described as having soft springs, for the comfort of their passengers or driver.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Vehicles with worn-out or damaged springs ride lower to the ground, which reduces the overall amount of compression available to the suspension, and increases the amount of body lean.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Performance vehicles can sometimes have spring rate requirements other than vehicle weight and load.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Wheel rate is the effective spring rate when measured at the wheel, as opposed to simply measuring the spring rate alone.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Wheel rate is usually equal to or considerably less than the spring rate.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Commonly, springs are mounted on control arms, swing arms or some other pivoting suspension member.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Consider the example above, where the spring rate was calculated to be 500 lbs/inch (87.5 N/mm), if one were to move the wheel 1 in (2.5 cm) (without moving the car), the spring more than likely compresses a smaller amount.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] If the spring moved 0.75 in (19 mm), the lever arm ratio would be 0.75:1.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The wheel rate is calculated by taking the square of the ratio (0.5625) times the spring rate, thus obtaining 281.25 lbs/inch (49.25 N/mm).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The ratio is squared because it has two effects on the wheel rate: it applies to both the force and the distance traveled.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Wheel rate on independent suspension is fairly straightforward.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] However, special consideration must be taken with some non-independent suspension designs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] When viewed from the front or rear, the wheel rate can be measured by the means above.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Yet, because the wheels are not independent, when viewed from the side under acceleration or braking, the pivot point is at infinity (because both wheels have moved) and the spring is directly inline with the wheel contact patch.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The result is often, that the effective wheel rate under cornering is different from what it is under acceleration and braking.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This variation in wheel rate may be minimised by locating the spring as close to the wheel as possible.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Wheel rates are usually summed and compared with the sprung mass of a vehicle to create a "ride rate" and the corresponding suspension natural frequency in ride (also referred to as "heave").
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This can be useful in creating a metric for suspension stiffness and travel requirements for a vehicle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Roll rate is analogous to a vehicle's ride rate, but for actions that include lateral accelerations, causing a vehicle's sprung mass to roll.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] It is expressed as torque per degree of roll of the vehicle sprung mass.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] It is influenced by factors including but not limited to vehicle sprung mass, track width, CG height, spring and damper rates, roll centre heights of front and rear, anti-roll bar stiffness and tire pressure/construction.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The roll rate of a vehicle can, and usually, does differ front-to-rear, which allows for the tuning ability of a vehicle for transient and steady-state handling.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The roll rate of a vehicle does not change the total amount of weight transfer on the vehicle, but shifts the speed and percentage of weight transferred on a particular axle to another axle through the vehicle chassis.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Generally, the higher the roll rate on an axle of a vehicle, the faster and higher percentage the weight transfer on that axle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] By 2021, some vehicles were offering **dynamic roll control** with ride-height adjustable air suspension and adaptive dampers.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Roll couple percentage is a simplified method of describing lateral load transfer distribution front to rear, and subsequently handling balance.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] It is the effective wheel rate, in roll, of each axle of the vehicle as a ratio of the vehicle's total roll rate.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] It is commonly adjusted through the use of anti-roll bars, but can also be changed through the use of different springs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Weight transfer during cornering, acceleration, or braking is usually calculated per individual wheel, and compared with the static weights for the same wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The total amount of weight transfer is only affected by four factors: the distance between wheel centers (wheelbase in the case of braking, or track width in the case of cornering), the height of the center of gravity, the mass of the vehicle, and the amount of acceleration experienced.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The speed at which weight transfer occurs, as well as through which components it transfers, is complex, and is determined by many factors; including, but not limited to: roll center height, spring and damper rates, anti-roll bar stiffness, and the kinematic design of suspension links.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Unsprung weight transfer is calculated based on weight of the vehicle's components that are not supported by the springs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This includes tires, wheels, brakes, spindles, half the control arm's weight, and other components.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] These components are then (for calculation purposes) assumed to be connected to a vehicle with zero sprung weight.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] They are then put through the same dynamic loads.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The weight transfer for cornering in the front would be equal to the total unsprung front weight times the G-force times the front unsprung center of gravity height divided by the front track width.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Sprung weight transfer is the weight transferred by only the weight of the vehicle resting on its springs, and not by total vehicle weight.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Calculating this requires knowing the vehicle's sprung weight (total weight less the unsprung weight), the front and rear roll center heights, and the sprung center of gravity height (used to calculate the roll moment arm length).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Calculating the front and rear sprung weight transfer will also require knowing the roll couple percentage.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The roll axis is the line through the front and rear roll centers that the vehicle rolls around during cornering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The distance from this axis to the sprung center of gravity height is the roll moment arm length.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The total sprung weight transfer is equal to the G-force times the sprung weight times the roll moment arm length divided by the effective track width.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The front sprung weight transfer is calculated by multiplying the roll couple percentage times the total sprung weight transfer.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The rear is the total minus the front transfer.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Jacking forces are the sum of the vertical force components experienced by suspension links.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The resultant force acts to lift the sprung mass, if the roll center is above ground, or compress it, if underground.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Generally, the higher the roll center, the more jacking force is experienced.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Travel is the measure of distance from the bottom of the suspension stroke (such as when the vehicle is on a jack, and the wheel hangs freely) to the top of the suspension stroke (such as when the vehicle's wheel can no longer travel in an upward direction toward the vehicle).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Bottoming or lifting a wheel can cause serious control problems, or directly cause damage.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] "Bottoming" can be caused by the suspension, tires, fenders, etc. running out of space to move, or the body or other components of the car hitting the road.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Many off-road vehicles, such as desert racers, use straps called "limiting straps" to limit the suspensions' downward travel to a point within safe limits for the linkages and shock absorbers.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This is necessary, since these trucks are intended to travel over very rough terrain at high speeds, and even become airborne at times.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Without something to limit the travel, the suspension bushings would take all the force, when suspension reaches "full droop", and it can even cause the coil springs to come out of their "buckets", if they are held in by compression forces only.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] A limiting strap is a simple strap, often from nylon of a predetermined length, that stops downward movement at a pre-set point before theoretical maximum travel is reached.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Without bump-stops, a vehicle that "bottoms out", will experience a very hard shock when the suspension contacts the bottom of the frame or body, which is transferred to the occupants and every connector and weld on the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Factory vehicles often come with plain rubber "nubs" to absorb the worst of the forces, and insulate the shock.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] A desert race vehicle, which must routinely absorb far higher impact forces, might be provided with pneumatic or hydro-pneumatic bump-stops.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] These are essentially miniature shock absorbers (dampers) that are fixed to the vehicle in a location, such, that the suspension will contact the end of the piston when it nears the upward travel limit.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Damping is the control of motion or oscillation, as seen with the use of hydraulic gates and valves in a vehicle's shock absorber.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This may also vary, intentionally or unintentionally.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Like spring rate, the optimal damping for comfort may be less, than for control.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Damping controls the travel speed and resistance of the vehicle's suspension.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] An undamped car will oscillate up and down.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] With proper damping levels, the car will settle back to a normal state in a minimal amount of time.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Most damping in modern vehicles can be controlled by increasing or decreasing the resistance to fluid flow in the shock absorber.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Camber changes due to wheel travel, body roll and suspension system deflection or compliance.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In general, a tire wears and brakes best at -1 to -2° of camber from vertical.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Depending on the tire and the road surface, it may hold the road best at a slightly different angle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Small changes in camber, front and rear, can be used to tune handling.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Some racecars are tuned with -2 to -7° camber, depending on the type of handling desired, and tire construction.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Often, too much camber will result in the decrease of braking performance due to a reduced contact patch size through excessive camber variation in suspension geometry.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The amount of camber change in bump is determined by the instantaneous front view swing arm (FVSA) length of suspension geometry, or in other words, the tendency of the tire to camber inward when compressed in bump.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Roll center height is a product of suspension instant center heights and is a useful metric in analyzing weight transfer effects, body roll and front to rear roll stiffness distribution.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Conventionally, roll stiffness distribution is tuned adjusting antiroll bars rather than roll center height (as both tend to have a similar effect on the sprung mass), but the height of the roll center is significant when considering the amount of jacking forces experienced.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Due to the fact that the wheel and tire's motion is constrained by the vehicle's suspension links, the motion of the wheel package in the front view will scribe an imaginary arc in space with an "instantaneous center" of rotation at any given point along its path.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The instant center for any wheel package can be found by following imaginary lines drawn through suspension links to their intersection point.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] A component of the tire's force vector points from the contact patch of the tire through instant center.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The larger this component is, the less suspension motion will occur.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Theoretically, if the *resultant* of the vertical load on the tire and the lateral force generated by it points directly into the instant center, the suspension links will not move.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In this case, all weight transfer at that end of the vehicle will be geometric in nature.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This is key information used in finding the force-based roll center as well.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Anti-dive and anti-squat are percentages that indicate the degree to which the front dives under braking, and the rear squats under acceleration.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] They can be thought of as the counterparts for braking and acceleration, as jacking forces are to cornering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The main reason for the difference is due to the different design goals between front and rear suspension, whereas suspension is usually symmetrical between the left and the right of the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The method of determining anti-dive or anti-squat depends on whether suspension linkages react to the torque of braking and accelerating.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] For example, with inboard brakes and half-shaft-driven rear wheels, the suspension linkages do not react, but with outboard brakes and a swing-axle driveline, they do.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] To determine the percentage of front suspension braking anti-dive for outboard brakes, it is first necessary to determine the tangent of the angle between a line drawn, in side view, through the front tire patch and the front suspension instant center, and the horizontal.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In addition, the percentage of braking effort at the front wheels must be known.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Then, multiply the tangent by the front wheel braking effort percentage and divide by the ratio of the center of gravity height to the wheelbase.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] A value of 50% would mean, that half of the weight transfer to the front wheels; during braking, it is being transmitted through front suspension linkage, and half is being transmitted through front suspension springs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] For inboard brakes, the same procedure is followed, but using the wheel center instead of contact patch center.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Forward acceleration anti-squat is calculated in a similar manner and with the same relationship between percentage and weight transfer.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Anti-squat values of 100% and more are commonly used in drag racing, but values of 50% or less are more common in cars that have to undergo severe braking.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Higher values of anti-squat commonly cause wheel hop during braking.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The value of 100% means that all of the weight transfer is being carried through suspension linkage.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] However, this does not mean that the suspension is incapable of carrying additional loads (aerodynamic, cornering, etc.) during an episode of braking, or forward acceleration.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In other words, no "binding" of the suspension is to be implied.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In some modern cars, flexibility is mainly in rubber bushings, which are subject to decay over time.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] For high-stress suspensions, such as off-road vehicles, polyurethane bushings are available, which offer more longevity under greater stresses.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] However, due to weight and cost considerations, structures are not made more rigid than necessary.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Some vehicles exhibit detrimental vibrations involving the flexing of structural parts, such as when accelerating while turning sharply.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Flexibility of structures, such as frames and suspension links, can also contribute to springing, especially to damping out high-frequency vibrations.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The flexibility of wire wheels contributed to their popularity in times when cars had less advanced suspensions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Automobiles can be heavily laden with luggage, passengers, and trailers.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This loading will cause a vehicle's tail to sink downwards.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Maintaining a steady chassis level is essential to achieving the proper handling that the vehicle was designed for.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Also, if the car's nose is too elevated when driving at night, oncoming drivers can be blinded by the headlight beam.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Self-levelling suspension counteracts this by inflating cylinders in the suspension to lift the chassis higher.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] For most purposes, the weight of suspension components is unimportant.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] But at high frequencies caused by road surface roughness, the parts isolated by rubber bushings act as a multi-stage filter to suppress noise and vibration better than can be done with only tires and springs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] These are usually small, except that the suspension is related to whether the brakes and differential(s) are sprung.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This is the main functional advantage of aluminum wheels over steel wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Aluminum suspension parts have been used in production cars, and carbon fiber suspension parts are common in racing cars.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Designs differ as to how much space they take up, and where it is located.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] It is generally accepted, that MacPherson struts are the most compact arrangement for front-engined vehicles, where space between the wheels is required to place the engine.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Inboard brakes (which reduce unsprung weight) are probably avoided more due to space considerations than to cost.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The suspension attachment must match the frame design in geometry, strength and rigidity.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Certain modern vehicles have height adjustable suspension in order to improve aerodynamics and fuel efficiency.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Modern formula cars that have exposed wheels and suspension typically use streamlined tubing rather than simple round tubing for their suspension arms to reduce aerodynamic drag.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Also typical is the use of rocker-arm, push rod, or pull rod-type suspensions, that, among other things, place the spring/damper unit inboard and out of the air stream to further reduce air resistance.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Production methods improve, but cost is always a factor.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The continued use of the solid rear axle, with unsprung differential, especially on heavy vehicles, seems to be the most obvious example.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Most conventional suspensions use passive springs to absorb impacts and dampers (or shock absorbers) to control spring motions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Some notable exceptions are hydropneumatic systems, which can be treated as an integrated unit of gas spring and damping components, used by the French manufacturer Citroën; and the hydrolastic, hydragas and rubber cone systems used by the British Motor Corporation, most notably on the Mini.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Traditional springs and dampers are referred to as passive suspensions — most vehicles are suspended in this manner.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Shock absorbers damp out the (otherwise simple harmonic) motions of a vehicle up and down on its springs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] They must also damp out much of the wheel bounce when the unsprung weight of a wheel, hub, axle, and sometimes brakes and the differential bounces up and down on the springiness of a tire.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] If suspension is externally controlled, then it is a semi-active or active suspension — the suspension is reacting to signals from an electronic controller.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] For example, a hydropneumatic Citroën will "know" how far off the ground the car is supposed to be, and constantly resets to achieve that level, regardless of load.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] However, this type of suspension will *not* instantly compensate for body roll due to cornering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Citroën's system adds about 1% to the cost of the car versus passive steel springs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Semi-active suspensions include devices, such as air springs and switchable shock absorbers, various self-levelling solutions, as well as systems, like hydropneumatic, hydrolastic, and hydragas suspensions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Toyota introduced switchable shock absorbers in the 1983 Soarer.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Delphi currently sells shock absorbers filled with a magneto-rheological fluid, whose viscosity can be changed electromagnetically — thereby giving variable control without switching valves, which is faster and thus more effective.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Fully active suspension systems use electronic monitoring of vehicle conditions, coupled with the means to change the behavior of vehicle suspension in real time to directly control the motion of the car.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Lotus Cars developed several prototypes from 1982 onwards, and introduced them to Formula One, where they have been fairly effective, but have now been banned.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Nissan introduced low-bandwidth active suspension *circa* 1990 as an option that added an extra 20% to the price of luxury models.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Citroën has also developed several active suspension models (see hydractive).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] A fully active system from Bose Corporation, announced in 2009, uses linear electric motors in place of hydraulic or pneumatic actuators that have generally been used up until recently.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Mercedes introduced an active suspension system called Active Body Control in its top-of-the-line Mercedes-Benz CL-Class in 1999.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Several electromagnetic suspensions have also been developed for vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Examples include the electromagnetic suspension of Bose, and the electromagnetic suspension developed by prof.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In addition, the new Michelin wheel with embedded suspension functioning on an electric motor is also similar.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] With the help of a control system, various semi-active/active suspensions realize an improved design compromise among different vibration modes of the vehicle; namely: bounce, roll, pitch and warp modes.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] However, the applications of these advanced suspensions are constrained by cost, packaging, weight, reliability, and/or other challenges.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Interconnected suspension, unlike semi-active/active suspensions, could easily decouple different vehicle vibration modes in a passive manner.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Interconnections can be realized by various means, such as mechanical, hydraulic, and pneumatic.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Anti-roll bars are one of the typical examples of mechanical interconnections, while it has been stated, that fluidic interconnections offer greater potential and flexibility in improving both the stiffness and damping properties.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Considering the considerable commercial potentials of hydro-pneumatic technology (Corolla, 1996), interconnected hydropneumatic suspensions have also been explored in some recent studies, and their potential benefits in enhancing vehicle ride and handling have been demonstrated.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The control system can also be used for further improving performance of interconnected suspensions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Apart from academic research, an Australian company Kinetic had some success with various passive or semi-active systems (WRC: three Championships; the Dakar Rally: two Championships; Lexus GX470 2004 as the 4×4 of the year with KDSS; the 2005 PACE award).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] These systems by Kinetic generally decouple at least two vehicle modes (roll, warp (articulation), pitch, and/or heave (bounce)) to simultaneously control each mode's stiffness and damping by using interconnected shock absorbers, and other methods.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In 1999, Kinetic was bought out by Tenneco.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Later developments by the Catalan company Creuat have devised a simpler system design based on single-acting cylinders.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] After some projects on competition, Creuat is active in providing retrofit systems for some vehicle models.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Historically, the first mass-production car with front-to-rear mechanical interconnected suspension was the 1948 Citroën 2CV.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Suspension in the 2CV was extremely soft — the longitudinal link was making pitch softer, instead of making roll stiffer.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] It relied on extreme anti-dive and anti-squat geometries to compensate for that.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This resulted in a softer axle-crossing stiffness that anti-roll bars would have otherwise compromised.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The leading arm / trailing arm swinging arm, fore-aft linked suspension system, together with in-board front brakes, had a much smaller unsprung weight than existing coil spring or leaf designs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The interconnection transmitted some of the force deflecting a front wheel up over a bump, to push the rear wheel down on the same side.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] When the rear wheel met that bump a moment later, it did the same in reverse, keeping the car level front to rear.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The 2CV had a design brief to be able to be driven at speed over a ploughed field, such as by a farmer transporting chicken eggs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] It originally featured friction dampers and tuned mass dampers.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Later models had tuned mass dampers at the front with telescopic dampers/shock absorbers front and rear.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] British Motor Corporation was also an early adopter of interconnected suspension.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] A system dubbed *Hydrolastic* was introduced in 1962 on Morris 1100, and went on to be used on a variety of BMC models.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] *Hydrolastic* was developed by suspension engineer Alex Moulton, and used rubber cones as the springing medium (these were first used on the 1959 Mini) with suspension units on each side connected to each other by a fluid-filled pipe.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The fluid transmitted the force of road bumps from one wheel to the other (on the same principle as Citroën 2CV's mechanical system described above), and because each suspension unit contained valves to restrict the flow of fluid, also served as a shock absorber.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Moulton went on to develop a replacement for *Hydrolastic* for BMC's successor British Leyland.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This system, manufactured under licence by Dunlop in Coventry, called *Hydragas*, worked with the same principle, but instead of rubber spring units, it used metal spheres divided internally by a rubber diaphragm.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The top half contained pressurised gas, and the lower half the same fluid as used on the *Hydrolastic* system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The fluid transmitted suspension forces between the units on each side, whilst the gas acted as the springing medium through the diaphragm.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This is the same principle as the Citroën hydropneumatic system, and provides similar ride quality, but is self-contained, and does not require an engine-driven pump to provide hydraulic pressure.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The downside is, that *Hydragas* is, unlike the Citroën system, not height-adjustable, or self-levelling.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] *Hydragas* was introduced in 1973 on Austin Allegro, and was used on several models; the last car to use it being MG F in 2002.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The system was changed in favour of coil springs over dampers due to cost reasons towards the end of the vehicle's life.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] When it was decommissioned in 2006, the *Hydragas* manufacturing line was over 40 years old.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Some of the last post-war Packard models also featured interconnected suspension.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Suspension systems can be broadly classified into two subgroups: dependent and independent.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] These terms refer to the ability of opposite wheels to move independently of each other.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] A *dependent suspension* normally has a beam (a simple 'cart' axle) or a (driven) live axle that holds wheels parallel to each other and perpendicular to the axle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] When the camber of one wheel changes, the camber of the opposite wheel changes in the same way (by convention, on one side, this is a positive change in the camber, and on the other side, this a negative change).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] De Dion suspensions are also in this category, as they rigidly connect the wheels together.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Dependent systems may be differentiated by the system of linkages used to locate them, both longitudinally and transversely.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Often, both functions are combined in a set of linkages.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In a front-engine rear-drive vehicle, dependent rear suspension is either "live-axle" or deDion axle, depending on whether or not differential is carried on the axle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Live-axle is simpler, but unsprung weight contributes to wheel bounce.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Because it assures constant camber, dependent (and semi-independent) suspension is most common on vehicles that need to carry large loads as a proportion of the vehicle's weight, that have relatively soft springs and that do not (for cost and simplicity reasons) use active suspensions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The use of dependent front suspension has become limited to heavier commercial vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Because the wheels are not constrained to remain perpendicular to a flat road surface in turning, braking, and varying load conditions, control of the wheel camber is an important issue.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Swinging-arm was common in small cars that were sprung softly, and could carry large loads, because the camber is independent of load.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Some active and semi-active suspensions maintain ride height, and therefore the camber, independent of load.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In sports cars, optimal camber change when turning, is more important.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Wishbone and multi-link allow the engineer more control over the geometry, to arrive at the best compromise, than swing axle, MacPherson strut, or swinging arm do; however, the cost and space requirements may be greater.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Semi-trailing arm is in between, being a variable compromise between the geometries of swinging arm and swing axle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In semi-independent suspensions, the wheels of an axle are able to move relative to one another, as in an independent suspension, but the position of one wheel has an effect on the position and attitude of the other wheel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This effect is achieved through the twisting or deflecting of suspension parts under load.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The most common type of semi-independent suspension is the twist beam.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The **Tilting Suspension System** (also known as the **Leaning Suspension System**) is not a different type or geometry of construction; moreover, it is a technology addition to the conventional suspension system.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This kind of suspension system mainly consists of independent suspension (e.g., MacPherson strut, A-arm (double wishbone)).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] With the addition of these suspension systems, there is a further tilting or leaning mechanism that connects the suspension system with the vehicle body (chassis).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The tilting suspension system improves stability, traction, the turning radius of a vehicle, and the comfort of riders as well.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] While turning right or left, passengers or objects on a vehicle feel the G-force or inertial force outward the radius of the curvature, which is why two-wheeler riders (motorbikes) lean towards the center of curvature while turning, which improves stability and decreases the chances of toppling.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] But vehicles with more than two wheels, and equipped with a conventional suspension system, could not do the same until now, so the passengers feel the outward inertial force, which reduces the stability of riders and their comfort as well.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This kind of tilting suspension system is the solution to the problem.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] If the road does not have super-elevation or banking, it will not affect the comfort with this suspension system, the vehicle tilt and decrease in the height of the center of gravity with an increase in stability.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This suspension is also used in fun vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Some trains also use tilting suspension (Tilting Train) which increases the speed at cornering.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The **rocker-bogie** system is a suspension arrangement, in which there are some trailing arms fitted with some idler wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Due to articulation between the driving section and the followers, this suspension is very flexible.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This kind of suspension is appropriate for extremely rough terrain.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This kind of suspension was used in the *Curiosity* rover.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Some vehicles, such as trains, run on long rail tracks fixed to the ground; and some, such as tractors, snow vehicles, and tanks run on continuous tracks that are part of the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Although either sort helps to smooth the path and reduce ground pressure, many of the same considerations apply.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Military armoured fighting vehicles (AFVs), including tanks, have specialized suspension requirements.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] They can weigh more than seventy tons, and are required to move as quickly as possible over very rough or soft ground.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Their suspension components must be protected from land mines and antitank weapons.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Tracked AFVs can have as many as nine road wheels on each side.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Many wheeled AFVs have six or eight large wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Some have a Central Tire Inflation System to reduce ground loading on poor surfaces.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Some wheels are too big and too confined to turn, so skid steering is used with some wheeled, as well as with tracked vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The earliest tanks of World War I had fixed suspension with no designed movement whatsoever.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This unsatisfactory situation was improved with leaf spring or coil spring suspensions adopted from agricultural, automotive, or railway machinery, but even these had very limited travel.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Speeds increased due to more powerful engines, and the quality of ride had to be improved.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] In the 1930s, the Christie suspension was developed, which allowed the use of coil springs inside a vehicle's armored hull, by changing the direction of force deforming the spring, using a bell crank.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The T-34's suspension was directly descended from Christie designs.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Horstmann suspension was a variation which used a combination of bell crank and exterior coil springs, in use from the 1930s to the 1990s.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The bogie, but nonetheless independent, suspensions of M3 Lee/Grant and M4 Sherman vehicles was similar to the Hortsmann type, with suspension sequestered within the track oval.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Torsion-bar suspension, sometimes including shock absorbers, has been the dominant heavy armored vehicle suspension since World War II.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Torsion bars may take space under or near the floor, which may interfere with making the tank low to reduce exposure.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] As with cars, wheel travel and spring rate affect the bumpiness of ride, and the speed at which rough terrain can be negotiated.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] It may be significant, that a smooth ride, which is often associated with comfort, increases the accuracy when firing on the move.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] It also reduces shock on optics and other equipment.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] The unsprung weight and track link weight may limit speed on roads, and can affect the useful lifetime of the vehicle's track, and its other components.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Most German WWII half-tracks and their tanks introduced during the war, such as the Panther tank, had overlapping and sometimes interleaved road wheels to distribute the load more evenly on the tank's track, and therefore on the ground.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] This apparently made a significant contribution to speed, range and track life, as well as providing a continuous band of protection.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] It has not been used since the end of that war, probably due to the maintenance requirements of more complicated mechanical parts working in mud, sand, rocks, snow, and ice; as well as due to cost.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] Rocks and frozen mud often got stuck between the overlapping wheels, which could prevent them from turning, or would cause damage to the road wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/suspension-vehicle] If one of the interior road wheels were damaged, it would require other road wheels to be removed in order to access the damaged road wheel, making the process more complicated and time-consuming.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/tire-model] In vehicle dynamics, a **tire model** is a type of multibody simulation used to simulate the behavior of tires.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/tire-model] In current vehicle simulator models, the tire model is the weakest and most difficult part to simulate.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/tire-model] Tire models can be classified on their accuracy and complexity, in a spectrum that goes from more simple empirical models to more complex physical models that are theoretically grounded.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/tire-model] Pacejka's *Magic Formula*, while physically based models include brush models (although they are still quite simplified), and more complex and detailed physical models include RMOD-K, FTire and Hankook.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/tire-model] Theoretically-based models can be in turn classified from more approximative to more complex ones, going for example from the solid model, to the rigid ring model, to the flexural (elastic) ring model (like the Fiala model), and the most complex ones based on finite element methods.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/tire-model] Brush models were very popular in the 1960s and '70s, after which Pacejka's models became widespread for many applications.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/tire-model] Fully physics-based tire models have been typically too computational expensive to be run in realtime driving simulations.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/tire-model] For example, to since CDTire/3D, a physics-based tire model, cannot be run in realtime, for realtime applications typically an equivalent semi-empirical "magic formula" type of model, called CDTire/Realtime, is derived from it through experiments and a regression algorithm.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/tire-model] In 2016, a slightly less accurate version of FTire, a physics-based tire model, was adapted to be run in real time.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/tire-model] This realtime version of FTire was shown in 2018 to run on a 2,7 GHz 12 Core Intel Xeon E5 (2014, 22 nm process, about $2000), with 900 contact road/contact patch elements, a sample frequency of 4.0 kHz including thermal and wear simulation.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/tire-model] The typical tire model sampling rate used in automotive simulators is 1 kHz.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/tire-model] However, running at higher frequencies, like 2 kHz, might mitigate lowered numerical stability in some scenarios, and might increase the model accuracy in frequency domain above about 250 Hz.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] A **traction control system** (**TCS**), is typically (but not necessarily) a secondary function of the electronic stability control (ESC) on production motor vehicles, designed to prevent loss of traction (i.e., wheelspin) of the driven road wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] TCS is activated when throttle input, engine power and torque transfer are mismatched to the road surface conditions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] Typically, traction control systems share the electrohydraulic brake actuator (which does not use the conventional master cylinder and servo) and wheel-speed sensors with ABS.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] The basic idea behind the need for a traction control system is the loss of road grip can compromise steering control and stability of vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] This is the result of the difference in traction of the drive wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] The difference in slip may occur due to the turning of a vehicle or varying road conditions for different wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] When a car turns, its outer and inner wheels rotate at different speeds; this is conventionally controlled by using a differential.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] A further enhancement of the differential is to employ an active differential that can vary the amount of power being delivered to outer and inner wheels as needed.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] The predecessor of modern electronic traction control systems can be found in high-torque, high-power rear-wheel-drive cars as a limited-slip differential.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] A limited-slip differential is a purely mechanical system that transfers a relatively small amount of power to the non-slipping wheel, while still allowing some wheel spin to occur.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] In 1971, Buick introduced *MaxTrac*, which used an early computer system to detect rear wheel spin and modulate engine power to those wheels to provide the most traction.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] A Buick exclusive item at the time, it was an option on all full-size models, including the Riviera, Estate Wagon, Electra 225, Centurion, and LeSabre.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] Cadillac introduced the *Traction Monitoring System* (TMS) in 1979 on the redesigned Eldorado.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] When the traction control computer (often incorporated into another control unit, such as the ABS module) detects one or more driven wheels spinning significantly faster than another, it invokes the ABS electronic control unit to apply brake friction to wheels spinning with lessened traction.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] Braking action on slipping wheel(s) will cause power transfer to wheel axle(s) with traction due to the mechanical action within the differential.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] All-wheel-drive (AWD) vehicles often have an electronically controlled coupling system in the transfer case or transaxle engaged (active part-time AWD), or locked-up tighter (in a true full-time set up driving all wheels with some power all the time) to supply non-slipping wheels with torque.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] There are instances when traction control is undesirable, such as trying to get a vehicle unstuck in snow or mud.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] Allowing one wheel to spin can propel a vehicle forward enough to get it unstuck, whereas both wheels applying a limited amount of power will not produce the same effect.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] Many vehicles have a traction control shut-off switch for such circumstances.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] Generally, the main hardware for traction control and ABS are mostly the same.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] In many vehicles, traction control is provided as an additional option for ABS.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] In all vehicles, traction control is automatically started when the sensors detect loss of traction at any of the wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] Very effective yet small units are available that allow the driver to remove the traction control system after an event if desired.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] In Formula One, an effort to ban traction control led to a change of rules for 2008: every car must have a standard (but custom mappable) ECU, issued by the FIA, which is relatively basic and does not have traction control capabilities.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] In 2003, Paul Tracy admitted that CART teams used traction control in the nineties, a device that was not formally legal until 2002 (although the switch to single engine supplier for 2003 reverted the legalization).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] In 2008, NASCAR suspended a Whelen Modified Tour driver, crew chief, and car owner for one race and disqualified the team after finding questionable wiring in the ignition system, which could have been used to implement traction control.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] Traction control is not just used for improving acceleration under slippery conditions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] It can also help a driver to corner more safely.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] If too much throttle is applied during cornering, the driven wheels will lose traction and slide sideways.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] This occurs as understeer in front-wheel-drive vehicles and oversteer in rear-wheel-drive vehicles.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] Traction control can mitigate and possibly even correct understeer or oversteer from happening by limiting power to the overdriven wheel or wheels.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] However, it cannot increase the limits of frictional grip available and is used only to decrease the effect of driver error or compensate for a driver's inability to react quickly enough to wheel slip.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/traction-control-system] Automobile manufacturers state in vehicle manuals that traction control systems should not encourage dangerous driving or encourage driving in conditions beyond the driver's control.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] The aspects of a vehicle's design which affect the dynamics can be grouped into drivetrain and braking, suspension and steering, distribution of mass, aerodynamics and tires.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] Some attributes relate to the geometry of the suspension, steering and chassis.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] Some attributes or aspects of vehicle dynamics are purely due to mass and its distribution.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] Some attributes or aspects of vehicle dynamics are purely aerodynamic.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] Some attributes or aspects of vehicle dynamics can be attributed directly to the tires.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] Some attributes or aspects of vehicle dynamics are purely dynamic.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] The dynamic behavior of vehicles can be analysed in several different ways.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] This can be as straightforward as a simple spring mass system, through a three-degree of freedom (DoF) bicycle model, to a large degree of complexity using a multibody system simulation package such as MSC ADAMS or Modelica.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] As computers have gotten faster, and software user interfaces have improved, commercial packages such as CarSim have become widely used in industry for rapidly evaluating hundreds of test conditions much faster than real time.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] Vehicle models are often simulated with advanced controller designs provided as software in the loop (SIL) with controller design software such as Simulink, or with physical hardware in the loop (HIL).
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] Vehicle motions are largely due to the shear forces generated between the tires and road, and therefore the tire model is an essential part of the math model.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] The tire model must produce realistic shear forces during braking, acceleration, cornering, and combinations, on a range of surface conditions.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] Most are semi-empirical, such as the Pacejka Magic Formula model.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] Racing car games or simulators are also a form of vehicle dynamics simulation.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] In early versions many simplifications were necessary in order to get real-time performance with reasonable graphics.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] However, improvements in computer speed have combined with interest in realistic physics, leading to driving simulators that are used for vehicle engineering using detailed models such as CarSim.
[src:vehicle-dynamics-control/vehicle-dynamics] It is important that the models should agree with real world test results, hence many of the following tests are correlated against results from instrumented test vehicles.
